Cloned from https://github.com/philsbln/ipv6-app-testing/issues/25 in repo migration 

@spmzt I think we should test applications to work without the 127.0.0.0/8 range available.
This is a real problem for us in production. For example, in FreeBSD there is an option to assign IPv4 and IPv6 stacks in a jail and when operating in an IPv6-only environment you don't want to assign the IPv4 stack. For many basic services we use (for example, BIND or Nginx) we must change the default configuration to replace 127.0.0.1 with ::1 to make them work.

@tojens-ietf +1, as I have seen apps using addresses across the 127.0.0.0/8 space (not just 127.0.0.1) as a presumed constantly-available resource to achieve inter-process communication between processes of the same "app"

